With R Markdown we can explain as we go. Now lets look at the distribution of the speed and dist variables. Again, see the code and then the output:

2. Now fit a linear model on speed and dist using Rs lm() function

This will give an idea of how the speed of the car affects stopping distance:

mymod <- lm(cars$dist ~ cars$speed)
summary(mymod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = cars$dist ~ cars$speed)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -29.069  -9.525  -2.272   9.215  43.201 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) -17.5791     6.7584  -2.601   0.0123 *  
## cars$speed    3.9324     0.4155   9.464 1.49e-12 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 15.38 on 48 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6511, Adjusted R-squared:  0.6438 
## F-statistic: 89.57 on 1 and 48 DF,  p-value: 1.49e-12

The output above indicates the relationship can be described with this factor:
3.9324
Now instead of using Rs lm() function, Ill go through the model with manual matrix operations.

3. Try fitting the same model from scratch with linear algebra

Y <- as.matrix(cars$dist) # dependent in Y
X <- as.matrix(cars$speed) # one independent in X
colnames(X) <- c("speed")
X <- cbind(x0=1, X) # add a buncha ones to matrix X
b <- solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) %*% Y # ols matrix solution
b
##             [,1]
## x0    -17.579095
## speed   3.932409

We got the same coefficient:
3.9324
Pretty cool!

4. Next manually find the standard errors

# H <- X %*% solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) # hat matrix
# Yhat <- H %*% Y # predictions

Yhat <- X %*% solve(t(X) %*% X) %*% t(X) %*% Y # predictions
R <- Y - Yhat # residual errors
MSE <- sum(R^2) / (nrow(X) - ncol(X) + 1 -1) # df = n - m

# added ones to matrix X so ??? add 1 df back in 
# ncol(x) doesn't include Y so ??? subtract an extra 1 df

var_bhat <- MSE * (solve(t(X) %*% X)) # variance
SE <- sqrt(diag(var_bhat)) # extract standard errors
SE
##        x0     speed 
## 6.7584402 0.4155128

This SE vector exactly matches the lm() results.
The SE on speed is:
.4155

5. Fit with estimatr package, and HC1 robust standard errors to replicate STATAs r switch

myrobustmod <- lm_robust(cars$dist ~ cars$speed, se_type = "stata")
summary(myrobustmod)
## 
## Call:
## lm_robust(formula = cars$dist ~ cars$speed, se_type = "stata")
## 
## Standard error type:  HC1 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error  Pr(>|t|) CI Lower CI Upper DF
## (Intercept)  -17.579     5.6561 3.163e-03  -28.952   -6.207 48
## cars$speed     3.932     0.4069 7.654e-13    3.114    4.751 48
## 
## Multiple R-squared:  0.6511 ,    Adjusted R-squared:  0.6438 
## F-statistic:  93.4 on 1 and 48 DF,  p-value: 7.654e-13

SE on speed is:
.4069
While SE from the lm() model was:
.4155
Robust SE is one way to handle heteroscedasticity.

6. Should a linear model even be used here?

ggplot(cars, aes(x=speed, y=dist)) + geom_smooth(size=.5) + geom_point() + geom_abline(intercept=-17.579, slope=3.9324, color="purple1", size=1.5, alpha=.4) + labs(x="Vehicle Speed", y="Stopping Distance", title="Visualize The Relationship") + theme_gdocs()

Excellent! Our linear model looks like a good starting point.
